metadata.name: Ecce Gratum #82
metadata.description:
"Ecce Gratum" is a symphony of colors and lines, a visual work that sings to the soul. The strokes of the brush are bold and confident, yet gentle and loving, like the notes of a symphony. The title, "Ecce Gratum", translates to "Behold the pleasing", and as you gaze upon this art, it is impossible not to be moved by its beauty and wonder. This painting is a celebration of life, a reminder to embrace the present and to find joy in the simple things. It is a call to look beyond the surface, to see the beauty in the world around us, and to let our hearts sing

Manu

A collector-led exploration of minimalist imperfect line work.

Palettes are named after native New Zealand birds and range from the subdued to the colorful.

There are no especially rare traits so mint what you love :)

metadata.name: VIBE #125
Possible Ways #89
metadata.description:
This project is written in javascript without using any other libraries, and it is an endless real-time software animation.

The appearance of each token is initially determined by the hash, but the size and positions of its elements change randomly over time, creating an infinite performance.

While working on this project, I was inspired by the elusiveness of the moment, that cannot be saved or predicted. It can only be experienced.

metadata.name: Dating an AI #138
metadata.description:
Audiovisual generative artwork. 

Spending a lot of time with something/someone who is how you want them to be, often equalizes them by adopting the other's appearance. This could become a blend of mirror relationship in pleasant solitude.

In this sense, the art piece shows a comic displaying vignettes between two almost identical characters, in a fast “stickman” aesthetic. It suggests a fluid, hopefully transcendent connection between a human character and an artificial intelligence.

Then we see these beings strangely mimicking each other, walking in a city that seems lonely, empty, from the perspective of the two characters: as if nothing else mattered more than themselves, leaving the rest of existence on a very distant plane.

Between them, dialogues of overlapping points and lines emerge. Like zeros and ones that embrace, mix and understand each other very well. Here the voices are electronic, minimalist. Abstractions that become even more abstract sounds, in search of a synchronicity and mutual empathy that grows towards who knows where.

This artwork is 100% code, made in p5.js.
Original piano sampler and synths programmed in the tone.js library.


[ Click ]  -> sound ON / OFF
[ s ] -> save 2160 × 3054px (in live view)
[ f ] -> fullscreen
[ p ] -> pause / play 

Note: This artwork is an animated piece, and requires a powerful GPU for optimal real-time playback. It is important to note that it may not run properly on mobile devices, especially not high-end ones.
It is recommended to run the piece in a new window from the “open” button.

metadata.name: Jajim #145
metadata.description:
The main idea of the "Jajim" is to divide a square into smaller parts in such a way that each variation has its original and unique composition. The role of lines is such that sometimes they help the dynamics of the composition and sometimes they appear in the form of texture and its contrast with empty spaces leads to the visual richness of the work. I avoided drawing various visual elements in favor of clarity of composition. Also, in order to avoid exaggeration, I used colors sparingly because I think they will have a stronger impact in their occasional presence.

Created using p5.js.

metadata.name: Chord Unknown #215
metadata.description:
The feeling of experimenting with an instrument you have not learned, and then suddenly striking an actual chord.

The code creates several grids and then applies one of six unique deformation techniques with varying intensity. It's a defined process of experimentation, and even though I'm the one that wrote the rules, each output breaks through somehow as a complete surprise to me. So when I see them, I get a Chord Unknown.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: COMPUTERS #123
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from pixel array computations and classic noise algorithms.

COMPUTERS is a meditation on the aesthetics of computing in all of its forms. It recalls the types of computation required to build temples, write complex texts, weave detailed textiles, and program computer games. Pixels have always existed in some form or another, before and after the screen. Every iteration of COMPUTERS suggests that computation is both contemporary and ancient.

Press 'p' or click to pause the animation.
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.
